        <tr>
          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              Status update / knowledge bomb<br /><br />Hit up Lowes this afternoon for supplies.  As a PSA, apparently copper prices are going up right now.  Ace just doubled their prices this week, but Lowes has not yet.  If you're thinking of doing a copper chiller, now might be a good time.<br /><br />Also interesting, apparently most of the soft copper tubing is refrigerant grade, which is allowed to contain lead, cadmium, arsenic, all sorts of fun stuff.  I guess to be food safe you need C12200 alloy, or one of the various potable water certifications.  At Lowes, the cheapest brand, JMF, ended up being the one to go with.  I called their customer service line, they answered the phone right away, and I read the SKU to them over the phone and they told me which ones were C12200.  Very cool customer service, so thumbs up to them, and the guy at Lowes who helped me track down all the mis-shelved variants.  20' of 1/4&quot; copper acquired for just under $14.<br /><br />The coil was basically already in the right shape, so I just widened it a little and stacked it around the outside of a sauce pot.  I didn't use any tube benders, so my in and out stems don't look very pretty since I went with gentle curves instead of 90 degree bends, but it will work.<br /><br />Total material cost: $38 including tax (plus driving to Lowes I guess, so a buck of gas).  I probably could have kept that under $30 for materials if our kitchen sink had a standard aerator attachment.  I had to MacGuyver something really weird together.  The plumbers epoxy is curing now, but I'll test it for being water-tight tomorrow.<br /><br />So... how to I clean this thing?  I assume that I should cleanse it somehow before using it with a food product.  Soak it in a bucket of vinegar?

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
    </table>
    
