              <div class="quotetitle">Frennzy wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">AFAIK, you have to send them out to be tested.  Most people just use published averages for each rhizome.<br /><br />Or they don't use them as bittering hops.</div><br />It looks like I might be able to get them tested for &lt;$30, so that's a possibility - but I strongly suspect I simply won't get around to it.<br /><br />What kind of range do you expect to see within a varietal? I've always just gone by what my local brew shop lists as the content; I've never really compared one season's crop to another. If we're talking about the difference between 6 and 7 AAU, then I don't care. With as slipshod an operation as I run, that won't even be close to the least precise part of the brew. If we're talking about 4 to 8 AAU, though, even I'll have to care.<br /><br />Although I suppose just not using them as bittering hops is a workable solution. I admit to being somewhat enthralled with the idea of increasing the &quot;home&quot; part of &quot;homebrew,&quot; but it really wouldn't be such a big deal to keep several ounces of (say) Galena on hand just for baseline bittering.<br /><br />I probably won't be able to resist at least one brew with the Centennial for bittering and the Cascade for finishing, though.

              

              
              
